<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Bodying Agent" class="currentChild" href="Bodying_Agent">Bodying Agent</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A substance added to a printing ink to increase its <a title="Viscosity" href="Viscosity">viscosity</a>. Bodying agents (such as <a title="Body Gum" href="Body_Gum">body gum</a> or <a title="Binding Varnish" href="Binding_Varnish">binding varnish</a>) increase an ink's <a title="Tack" href="Tack">tack</a>, and the increased viscosity allows the ink to print images and type more sharply. When added to lithographic ink, they prevent <a title="Emulsification" href="Emulsification">emulsification</a> and <a title="Ink Chalking" href="Ink_Chalking">ink chalking</a>, and improve drying. (See also <a title="Body Gum" href="Body_Gum">Body Gum</a> and <a title="Binding Varnish" href="Binding_Varnish">Binding Varnish</a>.) A bodying agent is also known as a <a title="Thickener" href="Thickener">thickener</a>. 
</p>
